reason_thou:
1. Understanding the Issue:
The crash occurs due to an out-of-bounds access on a SmallVector when indexing Entries[Pair.first] in BoUpSLP::isGatherShuffledSingleRegisterEntry. This indicates that Pair.first contains an index that is not valid for the current Entries vector.

2. Analyzing opt's Log:
The debug log shows the crash in isGatherShuffledSingleRegisterEntry during mask construction for shuffled gathers. The code remaps EntryLanes' Pair.first (which denotes the source entry index for each lane) based on which entries are used (UsedIdxs) and builds TempEntries accordingly. The crash stack points at Entries[Pair.first]->Scalars and Entries[Pair.first]->findLaneForValue, so Pair.first was not properly remapped to the new compacted Entries index space.

3. Root Cause Analysis:
EntryLanes stores Pair.first values that come from UsedValuesEntry, which refer to indices in a broader space than the local Entries vector. The current code attempts to remap Pair.first by looping I over 0..Entries.size() and replacing Pair.first when it equals I. However, Entries has already been filtered to only those indices for which UsedIdxs.test(I) is true. If Pair.first refers to an original index that is not within 0..Entries.size()-1 (because Entries is a subset and uses dense 0..N-1 now), the equality comparison will never trigger, leaving Pair.first pointing to an invalid index. Subsequent access Entries[Pair.first] asserts.
In short: The code assumes Pair.first indexes align with the current Entries indices and tries to update them via equality, but Pair.first encodes original indices from the broader UsedValuesEntry mapping. When Entries is compacted, Pair.first must be updated via a proper mapping from original indices to new compact indices. The current loop does not build or use such a mapping, hence the out-of-range index and assertion.

4. Proposed Edit Point(s):
- Edit Point 1 (lines 14671-14683 in llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp): Replace the ad-hoc Pair.first remapping with a robust map from original entry indices to compacted indices. Build DenseMap<unsigned, unsigned> OldToNew during TempEntries construction, then remap all Pair.first using this map. Also drop any EntryLanes whose Pair.first is not present in OldToNew (defensive).

New code block suggestion:
  // Iterate through all shuffled scalars and select entries, which can be used
  // for final shuffle.
  SmallVector<const TreeEntry *> TempEntries;
  DenseMap<unsigned, unsigned> OldToNew;
  for (unsigned I = 0, Sz = Entries.size(); I < Sz; ++I) {
    if (!UsedIdxs.test(I))
      continue;
    unsigned NewIdx = TempEntries.size();
    OldToNew.try_emplace(I, NewIdx);
    TempEntries.push_back(Entries[I]);
  }
  Entries.swap(TempEntries);
  // Remap lanes to the new compacted Entries indexing.
  for (std::pair<unsigned, int> &Pair : EntryLanes) {
    auto ItMap = OldToNew.find(Pair.first);
    if (ItMap == OldToNew.end())
      continue; // Lane refers to an entry we did not select; keep as-is (will be ignored later).
    Pair.first = ItMap->second;
  }

- Edit Point 2 (narrow fix within lines 14678-14681): Remove the existing loop that remaps Pair.first by comparing to I (which is incorrect after compaction). This prevents stale indices from persisting.

These changes ensure Entries[Pair.first] always indexes within Entries.size(), or the lane is skipped by subsequent logic when Entries.empty() or lanes mismatch.

5. Conclusion:
By introducing an explicit mapping from original entry indices to the compacted Entries indices and using it to remap EntryLanes, we avoid out-of-bounds access in Entries[Pair.first]. This fixes the assertion and aligns the mask construction logic with the filtered Entries subset, making isGatherShuffledSingleRegisterEntry robust against index space changes during compaction.

